6. Properties of Bernoulli Distribution
Property	Formula / Value	Description
Type	Discrete	Two possible outcomes
Parameters	p (probability of success)	0 â‰¤ p â‰¤ 1
Mean	E(X) = p	Expected success rate
Variance	Var(X) = p(1 - p)	Spread of data
Mode	1 (if p > 0.5) or 0 (if p < 0.5)	Most frequent value
Median	0 or 1	Central point
Range of X	0, 1	Only two possible values

7. Real-Life Examples
Scenario	Success (1)	Failure (0)	Probability (p)
Coin toss	Head	Tail	0.5
Exam result	Pass	Fail	0.7
Quality control	Defective	Non-defective	0.1

8. Relationship with Binomial Distribution
A Bernoulli distribution is a special case of the Binomial distribution with
n = 1
That is, Binomial(n=1, p) â‰¡ Bernoulli(p)

9. Summary
Measure	Formula	Description
Mean	p	Expected success probability
Variance	p(1 - p)	Measure of spread
SD	âˆš[p(1 - p)]	Spread in same units as X
Median	0 or 1	Middle value
Mode	1 if p > 0.5, else 0	Most frequent outcome

Key Takeaway: Bernoulli Distribution models a single trial with binary outcomes â€” it forms the foundation for many statistical and machine learning concepts such as logistic regression and binomial models.
